*  upstream-patch-signal
** Pattern: Upstream Patches as Consulting Signal
   + CONTEXT:
     A practitioner wants to signal expertise to potential
     clients or employers but dislikes self-promotion. Blog
     posts, talks, and social media feel performative.
   + IF:
     The practitioner uses open-source dependencies deeply
     enough to find bugs, missing features, or design
     improvements.
   + HOWEVER:
     Sending one patch to one project is invisible. Writing
     blog posts about capabilities feels hollow without
     evidence.
   + THEN:
     Systematically identify patch opportunities in the
     upstream dependency network. Prioritise patches to
     projects with commercial ecosystems (XTDB, Datahike,
     Logseq) or active communities (Reagent, Malli). Each
     merged patch is a permanent, verifiable signal that
     says "I understand your codebase well enough to
     improve it."
   + BECAUSE:
     A merged PR is the strongest possible consulting signal.
     It is not self-promotion — it is demonstrated competence,
     publicly verifiable, attached to a real codebase the
     client cares about. The practitioner's dependency graph
     IS their professional network; patches are introductions.
   + NOTE:
     The Drawbridge CIDER adapter is the prototype instance:
     a real gap (no existing adapter), deep expertise (daily
     use of Drawbridge in the stack), and high visibility
     (every CIDER user would benefit). Estimated effort:
     2-3 days. Signal value: permanent.
   + RELATED:
     - depositing/scan-talk-frame (scan identifies patch targets)
     - depositing/grant-to-pitch (patches demonstrate the same
       capability that grants propose)
     - war-machine/cardinal-directions (patches are depositing
       in the open-source economy)
